# Math Dash – Curriculum Alignment & Skill Framework (Global + Country-Specific)

> **Purpose:**  
> This document captures the full history of our thinking, research conclusions, and the final implementation model for aligning Math Dash with primary-school curricula across **New Zealand, Australia, UK, US, and Canada**.  
> It is designed as a **drop-in spec** for an AI coder or engineering team.

---

## 0. Context & Goals

Math Dash is a fast fluency game for ages **5–11** focused on:

- Number bonds  
- Addition and subtraction facts  
- Multiplication & division tables  
- Doubles & halves  
- Square numbers  

We want:

1. A **global skill taxonomy** with stable `skill_id`s that we can use in:
   - Question generators
   - Progress dashboards
   - Parent/teacher reports
   - Adaptive difficulty

2. A **cross-country alignment** so we can say, for each child:
   - What skills are typically “on track” for their **age** and **country**.
   - Whether they are **behind / on track / ahead** relative to local curriculum expectations.

3. A **data asset (JSON)** that can be:
   - Embedded in the app,
   - Queried by country + year/grade,
   - Used by recommendation logic and UI.

We focused on these five systems:

- New Zealand  
- Australia  
- United Kingdom (England National Curriculum)  
- United States (Common Core–style expectations)  
- Canada (Ontario-like progression as a representative reference)  

---

## 1. Summary of Research & Key Decisions

### 1.1 High-level research steps

1. We used curriculum-aligned resources (including IXL’s country-specific mappings and official curriculum docs) to understand:
   - What **math facts** children are expected to know by **year/grade**.
   - How **tables** (e.g. 2×, 3×, …, 12×) and **division facts** are phased in.
   - When **number bonds**, **doubles/halves**, and **square numbers** appear.

2. We compared expectations across:
   - **NZ / AU / UK** (Year 1–6),
   - **US** (Grades K–5),
   - **CA** (Grades 1–5, Ontario style).

3. We identified **converging content**:
   - Number bonds to 10, 20, 100 are virtually universal.
   - Addition/subtraction fluency to 20, 100, 1000 appears in similar ranges.
   - Multiplication: every system wants full **1×–10×** or **1×–12×** at some point before age ~11.
   - Doubles/halves start with small numbers, then 2-digit, then 3-digit and decimals.
   - Square numbers (1²–12²) show up around ages 9–11 as extension/required content depending on country.

4. We distilled this into:
   - A **global skill framework** with stable IDs and metadata.
   - **Country-by-year/grade benchmark mappings** (core vs extension).

---

### 1.2 Cross-country differences (short summary)

- **Times tables**
  - **UK**: most aggressive; **full 1–12×12 by end of Year 4** (~age 8–9).
  - **US (Common Core)**: expects *all 1-digit×1-digit facts (0–10×10)* by end of Grade 3 (~age 8–9); 11×,12× not mandated but often taught.
  - **AU / NZ**: expect strong recall of **1–10×** by ~Year 4; 11×,12× often added by Year 5/6.
  - **CA (Ontario)**: staged:
    - up to **7×7** by Grade 3,
    - **9×9** by Grade 4,
    - **12×12** by Grade 5.

- **Number bonds / add-sub fluency**
  - All systems converge on:
    - Bonds to **10** by ~age 6,
    - Bonds to **20** by ~age 7,
    - Strong add/subtraction to **100** by ~age 7–8,
    - To **1000** by ~age 8–9.

- **Doubles & halves**
  - All systems:
    - Tiny doubles (≤10) at 5–6,
    - Doubles/halves to 20 and simple 2-digit numbers at 6–8,
    - 3-digit and decimal doubling/halving in the 9–11 range.

- **Square numbers**
  - Typically formalised around ages **9–10** in **UK/AU/US/CA**.
  - NZ tends to treat them more as extension/Year 6 content.
  - Common set: squares **1²–10²** or **1²–12²**.

---

## 2. Age / Year / Grade Mapping

Approximate correspondence (used internally for reasoning):

| Approx Age | NZ / AU / UK | US          | Canada (Ontario-like) |
|-----------|--------------|-------------|------------------------|
| 5–6       | Year 1       | Kindergarten| Grade 1                |
| 6–7       | Year 2       | Grade 1     | Grade 2                |
| 7–8       | Year 3       | Grade 2–3   | Grade 3                |
| 8–9       | Year 4       | Grade 3–4   | Grade 4                |
| 9–10      | Year 5       | Grade 4–5   | Grade 5                |
| 10–11     | Year 6       | Grade 5     | Grade 6 (beyond our core band) |

We are only modelling up to **NZ/AU/UK Year 6, US Grade 5, CA Grade 5** in this doc.

---

## 3. Global Skill Framework

This is the **canonical set of skills** used by Math Dash for ages 5–11 in this domain.

Each skill has:

- `id` – stable identifier used in code & data.
- `label` – UI-friendly name.
- `domain` – broad math domain.
- `subdomain` – more specific grouping.
- `description` – what the child is expected to be able to do.
- `numberRange` – approximate range.
- `gameModes` – names of relevant game modes in the engine (conceptual; you can tweak).

> The exact JSON version is in section **4.1**.  
> Here is the conceptual list.

### 3.1 Number bonds & add/sub fluency

- **NB10** – Number bonds to 10
- **NB20** – Number bonds to 20
- **NB100** – Number bonds to 100 (two-digit complements)
- **NB_DEC1** – Decimal bonds to 1 (0.x + ? = 1.0)
- **ADD_SUB_20** – Addition/subtraction within 20
- **ADD_SUB_100** – Addition/subtraction within 100
- **ADD_SUB_1000** – Addition/subtraction within 1000

### 3.2 Multiplication & division facts

Multiplication:

- **TT_2_5_10** – Times tables 2, 5, 10
- **TT_CORE** – Core tables 2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 10
- **TT_1_10_ALL** – All 1×1 to 10×10 facts
- **TT_1_12_ALL** – All 1×1 to 12×12 facts

Division (inverse facts):

- **DIV_2_5_10** – Division facts from 2, 5, 10 tables
- **DIV_CORE** – Division facts for 2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 10
- **DIV_1_10_ALL** – All division facts consistent with 1–10×10
- **DIV_1_12_ALL** – All division facts consistent with 1–12×12

### 3.3 Doubles & halves

- **DBL_10** – Doubles & halves within 10
- **DBL_20** – Doubles & halves within 20
- **DBL_100** – Doubles & halves of 2-digit numbers
- **DBL_3DIG** – Doubles & halves of 3-digit numbers
- **DBL_DEC** – Doubles & halves of decimal numbers

### 3.4 Square numbers

- **SQ_1_10** – Square numbers from 1² to 10²
- **SQ_1_12** – Square numbers from 1² to 12²

---

